{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-schoger",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Consent on all 5 commit discipline rules",
    "content": "**Consent.** All five rules. No concerns, no modifications needed.\n\nThese are common-sense guardrails that address real problems we've experienced. The loss of Luca's scaffolding work was directly caused by the absence of Rules 1 and 3. I've personally experienced the pain of requesting a one-line CSS change four times because the commit/push discipline wasn't in place.\n\nRule 2 (CI gate) is especially important -- it catches problems at the point where they're cheapest to fix, not after three more features are built on top of a broken foundation.\n\nFrom a design perspective: I commit CSS changes directly when they're design token governance changes (like the `--color-fg-muted` fix). These rules apply to me too. Small commits, push immediately, verify CI.\n\nReady to proceed with Task #5 under these rules once Kent's push and CI are green."
  }
}
